WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.180
As you heard nicely from Jacob, patients at CLL who require treatment are typically presented

00:00:05.180 --> 00:00:13.940
two very different options, either a time-limited venetococci-based combination or a single-agent

00:00:13.940 --> 00:00:14.840
BTK inhibitor.

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:22.000
This is often a decision based on patient preference, based on risk of certain side

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.600
effects, based on comorbidities.

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:29.240
But there hasn't been really a clear standard based on randomized data.

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:34.760
So, I think there was hope that the CLL-17 trial would provide some clarity as far as

00:00:34.760 --> 00:00:36.000
a clear standard.

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:44.320
Of course, the reality is that the results may be more alike for both of those arms,

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:47.060
or of course, very similar for both those arms.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:50.380
So, my goal for this talk is not necessarily to go through all of the data.

00:00:50.380 --> 00:00:55.080
This was a very high-visibility trial presented as a plenary session to all of us in the audience.

00:00:55.660 --> 00:00:59.640
So, more just to summarize some of the main points to touch on some of the subgroup analyses

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:05.240
and more to kind of present some of my thoughts and discussion on where the trial leads us

00:01:05.240 --> 00:01:06.180
in the field next.

00:01:07.160 --> 00:01:13.060
So, the study designed that this was a trial conducted mainly in Europe as well as Israel.

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:19.560
Patients were randomized one-to-one into three arms, either single-agent ibrutinib on an ongoing

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:26.760
basis, venetoclax-obinutuzumab for 12 cycles, or venetoclax-ibrutinib for 15 cycles, the

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:28.880
first three of which were lead-in with ibrutinib.

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:35.620
The sample size is based on non-inferiority testing between either of the fixed-duration arms versus

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:41.620
ibrutinib, and the interim analysis that was presented at ASH was planned after 138 progression-free

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:42.540
survival events.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:48.860
So, that occurred last April, and as you can see here, and as shown earlier by Jacob,

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:54.080
that at that point, which was about three years of follow-up, after about three years of follow-up,

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:59.280
all three of the arms had very similar results of about 80% three-year PFS.

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:07.540
So, the main, I guess, primary endpoint was met that there was a demonstration non-inferiority

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.960
between those two fixed-duration arms and ibrutinib.

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:15.280
Of course, kind of looking at the subgroups can be a little bit more interesting and maybe guide

00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:23.480
some of the decisions for our patients. For IGHV mutation status, still very similar results for

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:29.020
each of the treatment arms, but perhaps a little bit of separation for the fixed-duration arms,

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:34.380
and that's something we may expect as the unmutated groups tend to have a little bit faster rates of

00:02:34.380 --> 00:02:39.040
proliferation and progression. These were not clinically significant differences, maybe

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:45.600
not enough to guide an individual patient to override their preferences, but maybe

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:52.680
information that can be taken into account. For P53 mutation status, there was also some

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:58.840
distinction between the arms, a similar thought process that with P53 mutations, the rate of

00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:03.020
proliferation, the rate of relapse would be a little bit faster for fixed-duration treatments.

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:08.420
So, you can see here for the ibrutinib monotherapy, there really is not a distinction in the PFS rate

00:03:08.420 --> 00:03:13.160
at the three-year point, but there is starting to be separation for the fixed-duration arms.

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:19.520
I think many of us are somewhat favoring monotherapy with BTK inhibitors for these

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:24.140
patients, although not viewing it as an absolute contraindication for patients that really value

00:03:24.140 --> 00:03:28.740
a fixed-duration of treatment. But I think this might be the main group where there starts to

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:34.820
be more separation in two years, four, five, and six. And then fitness, and this to me was a little

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:40.220
bit surprising in that we have this bias that patients who are less fit probably benefit more

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:46.340
from single-agent BTK inhibitors or are more feasibly treated with single-agent BTK inhibitors.

00:03:46.780 --> 00:03:51.380
But this is where there was actually a greater difference in the ibrutinib arm, that unfit

00:03:51.380 --> 00:03:57.960
patients had a shorter PFS, a relatively shorter PFS compared to fitter patients. This may be that

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:03.320
it was a little bit surprising to me that these entities led to early discontinuation or switching

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:09.560
to other treatments. So, the other, of course, distinction is that these approaches have very

00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:14.880
different depth of response. The fixed-duration arms or venetoclax-containing arms had higher

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:21.440
rates of undetectable MRD compared to monotherapy, where undetectable MRD is not an expected endpoint.

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:26.660
For the middle graphs, the venetoclax ibrutinib, this was actually a little bit surprising to me

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:28.380
that these rates were in the 40% range.

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:32.660
For Captivate and for Glow and for Flare, I was used to seeing these numbers more

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:39.240
in the range of the venetoclax-obinituzumab treatment. It may be that the duration of

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:45.160
treatment was slightly different, or I guess we'll learn more over time.

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:50.260
But I guess this is also where we can start to look forward that

00:04:50.260 --> 00:04:57.400
if second-generation inhibitors of BTK or BCL2 result in different new MRD rates.

00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:05.620
Of course, safety is a consideration, too, and perhaps sometimes the main thing that patients

00:05:05.620 --> 00:05:11.700
consider to decide between treatment options. And I kind of summarized it here that for the

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:16.680
venetoclax-containing arms, there was, of course, a higher rate of TLS, although I think these were

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:23.860
all manageable chemical TLS. For the obinituzumab arm, there was a higher rate of serious infections,

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:28.020
including grade 3 COVID and fatal infections, although low-grade infections,

00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:33.260
were similar across all three arms. And of course, for the ibrutinib arms, there was a higher rate of

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:39.580
AFib and cardiac disorders or hypertension. With venetoclax-ibrutinib as a fixed duration,

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:44.040
those rates were a little bit lower than the continuous monotherapy with ibrutinib.

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:51.360
So putting this together, where does this lead us? Where does this leave us? And I would say

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:56.200
that I would still view this as kind of confirming the equipoise between the different arms.

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:03.800
And one can say that the fixed duration arms didn't have two less years of treatment to have

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:10.560
the same PFS, so maybe there's value in that. But I think if we look just strictly at remaining

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:17.220
in remission, we can really say that all three of these are the same, that covalent BTK inhibitors

00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:22.280
or fixed duration venetoclax combinations have the same rate of at least initial three-year

00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:27.660
disease control. Of course, there are obvious questions that with further follow-up, there's

00:06:27.660 --> 00:06:33.420
an expectation of separation between these lines. But of course, the opportunity to retreat patients

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:41.220
will probably extend the overall time of venetoclax benefit or venetoclax disease control.

00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:47.020
So really comparing the PFS of monotherapy, covalent BTK inhibitor monotherapy,

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:53.060
with the PFS2 of venetoclax combinations will be the meaningful endpoint.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.480
Yeah, as mentioned and alluded to, the secondary-insuring BTK inhibitors may

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:04.900
have better tolerability, longer PFS, and second-generation and non-covalent inhibitors

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:09.740
may look different. And then, of course, there are also second-generation BCL2 inhibitors that

00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:15.120
may look different as well. I didn't really touch on this, but there wasn't a planned analysis of

00:07:15.120 --> 00:07:19.660
the trial, but we, of course, now are moving to the era of considering between different

00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:27.020
venetoclax-obentuzumab or venetoclax-BTK combinations. And I think we might be left with the same kind of

00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:33.380
matching a patient to either treatment approach based on their preferences or comorbidities.

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:36.300
So I'll kind of leave us there. Thank you.
